docs.abstract: As Mr. Walker, the Republican governor, seeks a third term, Democrats look for a way to successfully make an economic argument in a state where the indicators are strong.

docs.lead_paragraph: RACINE, Wis. — This city’s downtown was all but empty on a recent Sunday afternoon, but one storefront office was so packed with Democrats that people had to wait outside.

headline.main: Democrats Want to Beat Scott Walker. But the Wisconsin Economy Is a Hurdle.
headline.print_headline: Democrats Circle in Wisconsin.  Strong Economy Is an Obstacle.

docs.abstract: “I’m sorry I didn’t understand more,” Mr. Biden said about his hugs and kisses to women over the years. “I’m not sorry for any of my intentions.”

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Joseph R. Biden Jr. on Friday twice jokingly referred to complaints from several women that he had made them uncomfortable with his physical contact, and then offered a convoluted apology about their concerns and his behavior.

headline.main: Joe Biden Jokes About Hugging in a Speech, Then Offers a Mixed Apology

docs.abstract: A super PAC aligned with Democrats will steer $20 million into a campaign to mobilize midterm voters in traditionally Republican states.
docs.snippet: A super PAC aligned with Democrats will steer $20 million into a campaign to mobilize midterm voters in traditionally Republican states.
docs.lead_paragraph: A heavily funded Democratic group will spend tens of millions of dollars to mobilize voters in the Republican-leaning states where control of the Senate is likely to be decided this November, stepping in to fill a void left by years of decay in Democratic infrastructure at the state and local level.

headline.main: To Take the Senate, Democratic Group Will Spend Big in Red States
headline.print_headline: Democrats’ ‘Super PAC’ Takes Aim At Senate

docs.abstract: G.O.P. leaders and White House aides are trying to prepare the president for trouble in House and Senate races. But he is rejecting their grim prognoses and wants to start campaigning.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump is privately rejecting the growing consensus among Republican leaders that they may lose the House and possibly the Senate in November, leaving party officials and the president’s advisers nervous that he does not grasp the gravity of the threat they face in the midterm elections.

headline.main: Trump’s Role in Midterm Elections Roils Republicans
headline.print_headline: Anxiety in G.O.P.  As Trump Scoffs  At Midterm Risks

docs.abstract: Democratic leaders are intervening aggressively in California, where the state’s unusual voting system could undercut their chances in crowded congressional races.

docs.lead_paragraph: FULLERTON, Calif. — The Democrats’ message to Mai Khanh Tran was polite but unsparing. With half a dozen Democrats running for Congress in her Orange County district, they showed her a discouraging poll and argued that she could not win — and risked fracturing the party in the June primary election.

headline.main: Fearing Chaos, National Democrats Plunge Into Midterm Primary Fights
headline.print_headline: Democrats Push Some To Bow Out

Steve Bullock of Montana, a Democrat who has crusaded against the loosening of campaign finance rules, is suing the Trump administration to block it from eliminating a mandate that politically active nonprofit groups disclose the identities of their major donors to the government.

headline.main: Montana Governor Sues I.R.S., Warning of ‘Foreign Money’ in Elections

docs.lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg, the billionaire former mayor of New York City, has decided to throw his political clout and personal fortune behind the Democratic campaign to take control of the House of Representatives this year, directing aides to spend tens of millions of dollars in an effort to expel Republicans from power.

headline.main: Michael Bloomberg Will Spend $80 Million on the Midterms. His Goal: Flip the House for the Democrats.
headline.print_headline: In Midterms, Bloomberg Has Mission, and $80 Million, for Democrats
